{"title_page": "Peter Ostrum", "text_new": "{{short description|American child actor and veterinarian}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Peter Ostrum\n| honorific_suffix   = D.V.M.\n| image              = Peter Ostrum by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| alt                = A three-quarters bust portrait photo shows a middle-aged Caucasoid man looking to the photographer's right; he is wearing a blue-plaid collared shirt and a lanyard.\n| caption            = Ostrum in November 2017\n| birth_name         = Peter Gardner Ostrum\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1957|11|1}}\n| birth_place        = [[Dallas]], [[Texas]], US\n| residence          = [[Lowville (village), New York|Lowville, New York]], US\n| education          = Doctorate of Veterinary Medicine\n| alma_mater         = [[Cornell University College of Veterinary Medicine]] (1984)\n| occupation         = {{plainlist|\n* Actor (1971-1984)\n* Veterinarian (1984\u2013present) }}\n| employer           = {{plainlist|\n* Countryside Veterinary Clinic\n* Dairy Health & Mgmt. Services }}\n| known_for          = Acting in ''[[Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory]]'' (1971)\n| home_town          = [[Cleveland]], [[Ohio]], US\n| spouse             = Loretta M. Lepkowski\n| children           = 2\n}}\n\n'''Peter Gardner Ostrum''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|o\u028a|s|t|r|\u0259|m}};<ref name=\"20050717npr\" /> born November 1, 1957) is an American veterinarian and former [[child actor]] whose only film role was as Charlie Bucket in the 1971 motion picture ''[[Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory]]''. \n\nOstrum was 12 years old when selected by talent agents for ''Willy Wonka''.  Though he enjoyed the experience of shooting the film, he opted not to sign a three-film contract when it was over.  After eschewing a career in film and theatre, Ostrum became reluctant to speak about his one starring role.  In 1990, he began an annual tradition of speaking to schoolchildren about the film, and he became a subject of interest again when the 2005 film ''[[Charlie and the Chocolate Factory (film)|Charlie and the Chocolate Factory]]'' was released to theaters.\n\nOstrum became interested in horses when he returned from shooting ''Willy Wonka'', and was particularly influenced by the veterinarian that tended to them.  Receiving his [[veterinary physician|Doctorate of Veterinary Medicine]] from [[Cornell University College of Veterinary Medicine]] in 1984, {{as of|2005|lc=yes}} Ostrum practiced and lived in [[Lowville (village), New York|Lowville, New York]] with his wife Loretta ({{n\u00e9e|Lepkowski}}), and two children: son, Leif, and daughter, Helenka.\n\n==Personal life==\nPeter Gardner<ref name=\"2011 I Want It Now\" /> Ostrum was born in [[Dallas]]<ref name=\"2005-07-18 MSNBC\" /><ref name=\"2006-01-03 DMN\" /> on November 1, 1957 to Dean Gardner Ostrum (1922\u20132014) and Sarepta Mabel {{nee|Pierpont}} (born 1922).  He is the youngest of four children.<ref name=\"1996 GMMTB\" />  Ostrum was living in [[Cleveland]] at age twelve, a city of which he was described as a native by [[MSNBC]].<ref name=\"2005-07-18 MSNBC\" />\n\nOstrum married Loretta M. Lepkowski in {{birth based on age as of date|30|2018|01|28|noage=1|mos=1}}.  The couple have two children, Helenka and Leif, with the latter following his father onto stage as the [[leading actor]] in several [[South Lewis Central School]] [[musical theatre|musicals]].<ref name=\"2018-01-28 WDT\" />  The Ostrums lived in [[Lowville (village), New York|Lowville, New York]] as recently as 2005.<ref name=\"2005-07-18 MSNBC\" />\n\n==''Willy Wonka''==\nOstrum was in the sixth grade and performing at the [[Cleveland Play House]] [[children's theatre]], when he was noticed by [[talent agent]]s who were searching nationwide for the actor to portray Charlie Bucket in ''[[Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory]]''. The agents took [[instant camera|Polaroid photo]]s of Ostrum and recorded him reading from [[Charlie and the Chocolate Factory|the original novel]], then returned to [[New York (state)|New York]]. Two months later Ostrum was called to New York for a [[screen test]] where he sang \"[[My Country, 'Tis of Thee]]\",<ref name=\"2011 I Want It Now\" /> and a month after that he was contacted and given ten days to prepare to leave for filming.<ref name=\"avma20001101\">{{cite journal\n| date        = 2000-11-01\n| title       = Dr. Ostrum and the chocolate factory\n| journal     = Journal of the American Veterinary Medical Association\n| publisher   = [[American Veterinary Medical Association]]\n| location    = [[Schaumburg, Illinois]], U.S.\n| url         = http://www.avma.org/onlnews/javma/nov00/s110100g.asp\n| accessdate  = 2009-10-11\n| archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120524221856/http://www.avma.org/onlnews/javma/nov00/s110100g.asp\n| archivedate = 2012-05-24\n| url-status    = dead\n}}</ref>  Ostrum left for [[Munich]] on August 10, 1970.<ref name=\"1996 GMMTB\" />\n\n{{quote box\n | quote  = Peter was a child who acted&mdash;he wasn't a [[child actor]].  He had none of the obvious technique, tricks, or affectations of the kind that TV kid actors had, and continue to have.  He was genuine, and his sincerity as a person shines through in his performance.  He was an extremely intelligent kid, who was both self-aware and skilled at what he was doing.\n | source = Frawley Becker, ''Willy Wonka'' [[dialogue coach]]<ref name=\"1996 GMMTB\" />\n | width  =30%\n | align  =right\n | salign = right\n}}\nIn 2000, Ostrum recalled that shooting ''Willy Wonka'' in Munich was \"sort of like being an exchange student for five months\".  Fond memories of his five months in West Germany included watching the construction of [[Olympiapark (Munich)|Olympiapark]], for the [[1972 Summer Olympics]], and working with [[Gene Wilder]] and [[Jack Albertson]].<ref name=\"20050717npr\" /><ref name=\"avma20001101\" />  As Ostrum had not worked in film before, Wilder took it upon himself to instruct the young actor in the business.  Ostrum would later describe Wilder as a quirky yet gentle gentleman who \"treated people with respect and dignity.\"  The bond that developed between the two actors was such that, even though they never saw each other again after filming ''Wonka'', Ostrum described Wilder's 2016 death as \"like losing a parent\".<ref name=\"2016-08-30 Variety\" />\n\nOstrum was [[tutor]]ed on-set for three hours a day, though sometimes only for 30\u201360 minutes at a time.<ref name=\"2018-01-28 WDT\" />  Though in his audition he had been assured that his singing would probably be cut and [[dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbed]], it was Ostrum's own singing voice that made it to the screen&mdash;albeit significantly cut.<ref name=\"20050717npr\">{{cite news\n |title       = Original Charlie Revisits 'The Chocolate Factory'\n |first       = Jesse\n |last        = Baker\n |url         = https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4757256\n |format      = [[streaming media|streaming audio]]\n |publisher   = [[NPR]]\n |location    = New York City, U.S.\n |date        = 2005-07-17\n |accessdate  = 2009-10-11\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20101107003913/http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4757256\n |archivedate = 2010-11-07\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>  In a 2011 interview, Ostrum told the story of how director [[Mel Stuart]] gave him a [[clapperboard]] from the film, and later on asked him how he got it because he had forgotten that he had done so; it is Ostrum's only souvenir from the set.<ref name=\"20111018CTMG\">{{cite interview\n | last           = Ostrum\n | first          = Peter\n | last2          = Cole\n | first2         = Julie Dawn\n | subjectlink2   = Julie Dawn Cole\n | interviewer    = Chuck Thomas\n | title          = Peter Ostrum and Julie Dawn Cole interview Willy Wonka and the Chocolate Factory\n | url            = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OvY1EUkw2j8\n |via=[[YouTube]]\n | work        = Chuck the Movieguy's Celebrity Interviews\n | date           = 2011-10-18\n | accessdate     = 2011-10-30\n }}</ref>\n\nAfter he finished shooting ''Willy Wonka'', the then 13-year-old Ostrum<ref name=\"avma20001101\" /> declined [[David L. Wolper]]'s offer of a three-film contract.  The teenager confided in Frawley Becker, his ''Willy Wonka'' [[dialogue coach]], that he turned down the contract to retain \"the freedom to choose what he played, and in what picture.\"  (Ostrum and Becker remained friends through at least 1996.)<ref name=\"1996 GMMTB\" />  In January 2018, Ostrum said he sometimes misses acting\u2014though not its [[hurry up and wait|hurry-up-and-wait]] nature\u2014but feels he dodged having to make the transition from child- to adult-actor.<ref name=\"2018-01-28 WDT\" />\n\n{{as of|2018|01}}, Ostrum still received US$8\u20139 <!-- (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|8|2018}}\u2013{{Inflation|US|9|2018}} in {{Inflation/year|US}}) -->of [[royalty payment]]s about every three months.<ref name=\"2018-01-28 WDT\" />\n\n===Lasting effect===\n[[File:Child cast of Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory at the 2011 Wizard World Chicago (cropped).JPG|thumb|Ostrum (second from left) in 2011 with the ''Willy Wonka'' child cast|alt=Five middle-aged Caucasoid adults (two women and three men) in casual dress are behind a table, posing for a group photo.]]\nIn his [[senior (education)|senior year]], Ostrum was involved in film class and, at the interest of one of his instructors, looked back into theatre and acting.  After auditioning for, but not landing, several roles<ref name=\"nwtbaa\" /> (including for [[Alan Strang]]<ref name=\"1996 GMMTB\" /> in [[Equus (play)|''Equus'']] on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]), Ostrum decided not to pursue it further.<ref name=\"nwtbaa\">{{cite web\n| first       =Peter\n| last        =Ostrum\n| title       ='Never Wanted to Be an Actor'\n| url         =https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4757256\n| publisher   =[[NPR]]\n| location    =New York City, U.S.\n| accessdate  =2009-10-11\n}}</ref>  After putting his short film career behind him, Ostrum declined reporters and interviews, preferring not to speak on the subject;<ref name=\"avma20001101\" /> \"I wanted people to judge me on who I was, not what I\u2019d done\".<ref name=\"DEX20110410\">{{cite news\n |title       = Whatever Happened to Willy Wonka's Children?\n |first       = Bridgit\n |last        = Grant\n |url         = http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/239837/Whatever-happened-to-Willy-Wonka-s-children-\n |newspaper   = [[Daily Express]]\n |publisher   = [[Northern & Shell]]\n |location    = London, UK\n |accessdate  = 2011-04-10\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20121005034157/http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/239837/Whatever-happened-to-Willy-Wonka-s-children-\n |archivedate = 2012-10-05\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>  For some time, Ostrum even lied and told people that his brother, and not he, had starred in the film.<ref name=\"2005-07-18 MSNBC\" />  It took Ostrum years after moving to Lowville before he told anybody there about his one-time stardom; even his wife Loretta did not know about his role until he warned her about it just before she met his mother.<ref name=\"20050717npr\" />\n\nSince 1990, Ostrum has since spoken to students at Lowville Academy once a year&mdash;on the last day of school, as a special treat&mdash;about his experience in ''Willy Wonka'' as well as his work in veterinary medicine.<ref name=\"2005-07-18 MSNBC\" />  The students chiefly ask about the film's special effects, and Ostrum describes to them \"what happened to Veruca, how did Violet blow up like a blueberry, how did Charlie fly with Grandpa Joe, all those types of questions.\"<ref name=\"20050717npr\" />  Ostrum also accepted an invitation to appear at the 2018 [[Snowtown Film Festival]] in [[Watertown (city), New York|Watertown, New York]], answering audience questions after a screening of the film; \"it\u2019s in my backyard\u2014it's become a popular event in January and I like to support local events.\"  Ostrum said of the 2018 event that he enjoyed re-watching the film, and that people ask him \"great questions.\"<ref name=\"2018-01-28 WDT\" />  Ostrum has been called \"the most famous man in Lowville\", where the local [[video rental shop]] has twice worn out its [[VHS]] copy of ''Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory''.<ref name=\"2005-07-18 MSNBC\" />\n\nIn the run-up to the release of [[Charlie and the Chocolate Factory (film)|''Charlie and the Chocolate Factory'']] in 2005, Ostrum garnered a spate of attention that included seeing the film in New York City with [[NPR]] as well as being included in [[VH1]]'s list of \"100 Greatest Kid Stars\" (at 78th).<ref name=\"2005-07-18 MSNBC\" />  On the new film, Ostrum quoted fellow ''Wonka'' actor [[Julie Dawn Cole]], saying that \"It's sort of like going back to a house that you once lived in and it's been redecorated.\"  Ultimately, the media attention was so pervasive that Ostrum stopped answering his phone, and requested \"please, no more interviews.\"<ref name=\"20050717npr\" />\n\nIn January 2009, Ostrum teamed up with [[Dunkin' Donuts]] to hand out free rides on the [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]] (MBTA) at [[South Station]] in [[Boston]]; Ostrum's participation connected the MBTA's [[CharlieCard]]s he was handing out with his portrayal of Charlie Bucket in ''Willy Wonka''.  The promotion also gave out one \"golden ticket\", worth unlimited rides on MBTA and unlimited Dunkin' Donuts coffee for 2009.<ref name=\"DDyoutube\">{{cite video\n |people      = Ostrum, Peter; McCall Gosselin\n |date        = 2009-01-23\n |title       = Wonka's Charlie Bucket says to Boston commuters, \"You Kin' Do It!\"\n |url         = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iY6PfkhWQM0\n |format      = [[YouTube]]\n |publisher   = [[Dunkin' Donuts]]\n |location    = [[Canton, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n |accessdate  = 2009-11-13\n |archivedate = 2016-05-11\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20160511214653/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iY6PfkhWQM0\n |url-status     = dead\n}}\n</ref>\n\nIn October 2000, Ostrum and some of his co-stars from the film were scheduled to record an audio commentary for a special edition [[DVD]].<ref name=\"avma20001101\" />  In a 2010 interview, ''Wonka'' co-star [[Denise Nickerson]] (Violet Beauregarde) revealed that Ostrum had agreed to join her and [[Paris Themmen]] (''Wonka''{{'}}s Mike Teevee) for a reunion commemorating the 40th anniversary of the film's release in 2011.<ref name=\"NWIT20100928\">{{cite news\n |title       = 'Willy Wonka' child actress feeling better-than-blue about future film reunion\n |first       = Phil\n |last        = Potempa\n |url         = http://www.nwitimes.com/entertainment/columnists/offbeat/article_65aae4df-5683-5f3f-816a-2bef3f41d952.html\n |newspaper   = [[The Times of Northwest Indiana]]\n |publisher   = [[Lee Enterprises]]\n |location    = [[Munster, Indiana]], U.S.\n |date        = 2010-09-28\n |accessdate  = 2011-01-14\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120927065647/http://www.nwitimes.com/entertainment/columnists/offbeat/article_65aae4df-5683-5f3f-816a-2bef3f41d952.html\n |archivedate = 2012-09-27\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n==Veterinary career==\n{{quote box\n | quote  =I can remember the veterinarian coming out and taking care of the horses, and it made a huge impression on me, [...] This person really enjoyed what he did for a living.  My father was a lawyer, and I really didn't have a clue what he did all day.  But I knew exactly what the veterinarian did.  Someone making a living from something he enjoyed so much really sparked my interest.\n | source =2000 interview with Peter Ostrum<ref name=\"avma20001101\" />\n | width  =30%\n | align  =right\n | salign = right\n}}\nSoon after Ostrum returned home from filming ''Willy Wonka'', his family acquired a horse; while the teenaged Ostrum was interested in the horse, it was the animal's veterinarian that left a lasting impression on him.  Taking a hiatus from school between [[secondary school|high school]] and [[college]], Ostrum [[groom (profession)|groomed]] horses and worked at the Delaware Equine Center in [[Pennsylvania]].  Ostrum contemplated a return to [[Hollywood]], and even visited [[California]] for a week to \"test the waters\" there.  He ultimately decided to pursue a degree in [[veterinary medicine]] instead, feeling that he would forever berate himself if he didn't.  In 1984, Peter Ostrum received his [[veterinary physician|Doctorate of Veterinary Medicine]] from [[Cornell University College of Veterinary Medicine]].<ref name=\"avma20001101\" />\n\n{{as of|2019|08}}, Ostrum worked in [[Lowville (village), New York|Lowville, New York]] both as a veterinarian with the Countryside Veterinary Clinic (working mainly with horses and cows),<ref name=VetNews/><ref name=\"CVCLLP\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.cvcpets.com/our-doctors.pml\n |title       = Our Doctors\n |publisher   = Countryside Veterinary Clinic, LLP\n |location    = [[Lowville (village), New York|Lowville, New York]]\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170807030851/http://www.cvcpets.com/our-doctors.pml\n |archivedate = 2017-08-07\n |accessdate  = 2019-08-19\n |url-status    = live\n}}</ref> and a [[managing partner]] with Dairy Health & Management Services.<ref name=\"Dairy Health & Management Services\" />  Ostrum also took part in ''Veterinarians on Call'', a [[Pfizer]]-funded video series that highlighted the work of large animal veterinarians.<ref name=VetNews>{{cite web|url=http://veterinarynews.dvm360.com/dvm/article/articleDetail.jsp?id=754731&sk=&date=&pageID=3|work=veterinarynews.dvm360.com|title=Vets take the stage in new reality series|author=Stephanie Fellenstein |date=1 Jan 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503133209/http://veterinarynews.dvm360.com/dvm/article/articleDetail.jsp?id=754731&sk=&date=&pageID=3|archivedate=May 3, 2014|publisher=DVM360 Magazine}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<!-- dated references; sorted chronologically -->\n\n<ref name=\"1996 GMMTB\">{{cite book |last1=Kurtti |first1=Jeff |year=1996 |chapter=Chapter Six: Willy Wonka and the Chocolate Factory |title=The Great Movie Musical Trivia Book |location=[[New York City]] |publisher=[[Hal Leonard Corporation|Applause Books]] |pages=[https://archive.org/details/greatmoviemusica00kurt/page/103 103\u2013120] |isbn=1-55783-222-6 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/greatmoviemusica00kurt/page/103 }}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"2005-07-18 MSNBC\">{{cite news |date=2005-07-18 |title=Original Charlie Bucket keeps low profile |url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/8545067/ |url-status=dead |work=[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]] |location=[[Lowville (village), New York|Lowville, New York]] |publisher=[[MSNBC]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121124073720/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/8545067/ |archive-date=2012-11-24 |access-date=2018-10-30 |quote=Peter Ostrum turned down three-picture deal after original 'Wonka'}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"2006-01-03 DMN\">{{cite news |last1=Cavazos |first1=Norma |date=2006-01-03 |title=Television Q&A |work=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |issn=1553-846X}}</ref>\n\n<!-- <ref name=\"2010-04-23 Watertown Daily Times\">{{cite news |date=2010-04-23 |title=South Lewis Central School class leaders |url=http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/article/20100423/CURR04/304239991 |url-status=live |work=Watertown Daily Times |location=[[Turin, New York]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120223083216/http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/article/20100423/CURR04/304239991 |archive-date=2012-02-23 |access-date=2018-07-27 }}</ref> -->\n\n<ref name=\"2011 I Want It Now\">{{cite book |last1=Cole |first1=Julie Dawn |author-link1=Julie Dawn Cole |last2=Esslinger |first2=Michael |year=2011 |chapter=Munich |title=I Want It Now! |edition=First |location=[[Duncan, Oklahoma]] |publisher=BearManor Media |pages=52\u201354 |isbn=978-1-59393-074-5 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"2016-08-30 Variety\">{{cite magazine |last1=Lang |first1=Brent |date=2016-08-30 |title=Actor Who Played Charlie in \u2018Willy Wonka\u2019 on Gene Wilder Death: \u2018It\u2019s Like Losing a Parent\u2019 |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/gene-wilder-willy-wonka-peter-ostrum-1201847688/ |url-status=live |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |language=en |issn=0042-2738 |oclc=810134503 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203030611/https://variety.com/2016/film/news/gene-wilder-willy-wonka-peter-ostrum-1201847688/ |archive-date=2019-02-03 |access-date=2019-02-04}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"2018-01-28 WDT\">{{cite news |last1=Avallone |first1=Elaine M. |date=2018-01-28 |title=Dr. Ostrum relates to being Charlie Bucket following showing of film |url=http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/news03/dr-ostrum-relates-to-being-charlie-bucket-following-showing-of-film-20180128 |url-status=live |work=[[Watertown Daily Times]] |location=[[Watertown (city), New York|Watertown, New York]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309055736/http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/news03/dr-ostrum-relates-to-being-charlie-bucket-following-showing-of-film-20180128 |archive-date=2018-03-09 |access-date=2018-03-10}}</ref>\n\n<!-- undated sources sorted alphabetically -->\n\n<ref name=\"Dairy Health & Management Services\">{{cite web |url=http://dairyhealth.co/our-team/ |title=Our Team |publisher=Dairy Health & Management Services |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819152841/http://dairyhealth.co/our-team/ |archive-date=2019-08-19 |url-status=live |access-date=2019-08-19}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0652578}}\n* [http://www.cvcpets.com/ Countryside Veterinary Clinic, LLP]\n\n{{Good article}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ostrum, Peter}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American veterinarians]]\n[[Category:American male child actors]]\n[[Category:Cornell University College of Veterinary Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Cleveland]]\n[[Category:People from Lowville, New York]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Dallas]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American child actor and veterinarian}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Peter Ostrum\n| honorific_suffix   = D.V.M.\n| image              = Peter Ostrum by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| alt                = A three-quarters bust portrait photo shows a middle-aged Caucasoid man looking to the photographer's right; he is wearing a blue-plaid collared shirt and a lanyard.\n| caption            = Ostrum in November 2017\n| birth_name         = Peter Gardner Ostrum\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1957|11|1}}\n| birth_place        = [[Dallas]], [[Texas]], US\n| residence          = [[Lowville (village), New York|Lowville, New York]], US\n| education          = Doctorate of Veterinary Medicine\n| alma_mater         = [[Cornell University College of Veterinary Medicine]] (1984)\n| occupation         = {{plainlist|\n* Actor (1971)\n* Veterinarian (1984\u2013present) }}\n| employer           = {{plainlist|\n* Countryside Veterinary Clinic\n* Dairy Health & Mgmt. Services }}\n| known_for          = Acting in ''[[Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory]]'' (1971)\n| home_town          = [[Cleveland]], [[Ohio]], US\n| spouse             = Loretta M. Lepkowski\n| children           = 2\n}}\n\n'''Peter Gardner Ostrum''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|o\u028a|s|t|r|\u0259|m}};<ref name=\"20050717npr\" /> born November 1, 1957) is an American veterinarian and former [[child actor]] whose only film role was as Charlie Bucket in the 1971 motion picture ''[[Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory]]''. \n\nOstrum was 12 years old when selected by talent agents for ''Willy Wonka''.  Though he enjoyed the experience of shooting the film, he opted not to sign a three-film contract when it was over.  After eschewing a career in film and theatre, Ostrum became reluctant to speak about his one starring role.  In 1990, he began an annual tradition of speaking to schoolchildren about the film, and he became a subject of interest again when the 2005 film ''[[Charlie and the Chocolate Factory (film)|Charlie and the Chocolate Factory]]'' was released to theaters.\n\nOstrum became interested in horses when he returned from shooting ''Willy Wonka'', and was particularly influenced by the veterinarian that tended to them.  Receiving his [[veterinary physician|Doctorate of Veterinary Medicine]] from [[Cornell University College of Veterinary Medicine]] in 1984, {{as of|2005|lc=yes}} Ostrum practiced and lived in [[Lowville (village), New York|Lowville, New York]] with his wife Loretta ({{n\u00e9e|Lepkowski}}), and two children: son, Leif, and daughter, Helenka.\n\n==Personal life==\nPeter Gardner<ref name=\"2011 I Want It Now\" /> Ostrum was born in [[Dallas]]<ref name=\"2005-07-18 MSNBC\" /><ref name=\"2006-01-03 DMN\" /> on November 1, 1957 to Dean Gardner Ostrum (1922\u20132014) and Sarepta Mabel {{nee|Pierpont}} (born 1922).  He is the youngest of four children.<ref name=\"1996 GMMTB\" />  Ostrum was living in [[Cleveland]] at age twelve, a city of which he was described as a native by [[MSNBC]].<ref name=\"2005-07-18 MSNBC\" />\n\nOstrum married Loretta M. Lepkowski in {{birth based on age as of date|30|2018|01|28|noage=1|mos=1}}.  The couple have two children, Helenka and Leif, with the latter following his father onto stage as the [[leading actor]] in several [[South Lewis Central School]] [[musical theatre|musicals]].<ref name=\"2018-01-28 WDT\" />  The Ostrums lived in [[Lowville (village), New York|Lowville, New York]] as recently as 2005.<ref name=\"2005-07-18 MSNBC\" />\n\n==''Willy Wonka''==\nOstrum was in the sixth grade and performing at the [[Cleveland Play House]] [[children's theatre]], when he was noticed by [[talent agent]]s who were searching nationwide for the actor to portray Charlie Bucket in ''[[Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory]]''. The agents took [[instant camera|Polaroid photo]]s of Ostrum and recorded him reading from [[Charlie and the Chocolate Factory|the original novel]], then returned to [[New York (state)|New York]]. Two months later Ostrum was called to New York for a [[screen test]] where he sang \"[[My Country, 'Tis of Thee]]\",<ref name=\"2011 I Want It Now\" /> and a month after that he was contacted and given ten days to prepare to leave for filming.<ref name=\"avma20001101\">{{cite journal\n| date        = 2000-11-01\n| title       = Dr. Ostrum and the chocolate factory\n| journal     = Journal of the American Veterinary Medical Association\n| publisher   = [[American Veterinary Medical Association]]\n| location    = [[Schaumburg, Illinois]], U.S.\n| url         = http://www.avma.org/onlnews/javma/nov00/s110100g.asp\n| accessdate  = 2009-10-11\n| archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120524221856/http://www.avma.org/onlnews/javma/nov00/s110100g.asp\n| archivedate = 2012-05-24\n| url-status    = dead\n}}</ref>  Ostrum left for [[Munich]] on August 10, 1970.<ref name=\"1996 GMMTB\" />\n\n{{quote box\n | quote  = Peter was a child who acted&mdash;he wasn't a [[child actor]].  He had none of the obvious technique, tricks, or affectations of the kind that TV kid actors had, and continue to have.  He was genuine, and his sincerity as a person shines through in his performance.  He was an extremely intelligent kid, who was both self-aware and skilled at what he was doing.\n | source = Frawley Becker, ''Willy Wonka'' [[dialogue coach]]<ref name=\"1996 GMMTB\" />\n | width  =30%\n | align  =right\n | salign = right\n}}\nIn 2000, Ostrum recalled that shooting ''Willy Wonka'' in Munich was \"sort of like being an exchange student for five months\".  Fond memories of his five months in West Germany included watching the construction of [[Olympiapark (Munich)|Olympiapark]], for the [[1972 Summer Olympics]], and working with [[Gene Wilder]] and [[Jack Albertson]].<ref name=\"20050717npr\" /><ref name=\"avma20001101\" />  As Ostrum had not worked in film before, Wilder took it upon himself to instruct the young actor in the business.  Ostrum would later describe Wilder as a quirky yet gentle gentleman who \"treated people with respect and dignity.\"  The bond that developed between the two actors was such that, even though they never saw each other again after filming ''Wonka'', Ostrum described Wilder's 2016 death as \"like losing a parent\".<ref name=\"2016-08-30 Variety\" />\n\nOstrum was [[tutor]]ed on-set for three hours a day, though sometimes only for 30\u201360 minutes at a time.<ref name=\"2018-01-28 WDT\" />  Though in his audition he had been assured that his singing would probably be cut and [[dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbed]], it was Ostrum's own singing voice that made it to the screen&mdash;albeit significantly cut.<ref name=\"20050717npr\">{{cite news\n |title       = Original Charlie Revisits 'The Chocolate Factory'\n |first       = Jesse\n |last        = Baker\n |url         = https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4757256\n |format      = [[streaming media|streaming audio]]\n |publisher   = [[NPR]]\n |location    = New York City, U.S.\n |date        = 2005-07-17\n |accessdate  = 2009-10-11\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20101107003913/http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4757256\n |archivedate = 2010-11-07\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>  In a 2011 interview, Ostrum told the story of how director [[Mel Stuart]] gave him a [[clapperboard]] from the film, and later on asked him how he got it because he had forgotten that he had done so; it is Ostrum's only souvenir from the set.<ref name=\"20111018CTMG\">{{cite interview\n | last           = Ostrum\n | first          = Peter\n | last2          = Cole\n | first2         = Julie Dawn\n | subjectlink2   = Julie Dawn Cole\n | interviewer    = Chuck Thomas\n | title          = Peter Ostrum and Julie Dawn Cole interview Willy Wonka and the Chocolate Factory\n | url            = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OvY1EUkw2j8\n |via=[[YouTube]]\n | work        = Chuck the Movieguy's Celebrity Interviews\n | date           = 2011-10-18\n | accessdate     = 2011-10-30\n }}</ref>\n\nAfter he finished shooting ''Willy Wonka'', the then 13-year-old Ostrum<ref name=\"avma20001101\" /> declined [[David L. Wolper]]'s offer of a three-film contract.  The teenager confided in Frawley Becker, his ''Willy Wonka'' [[dialogue coach]], that he turned down the contract to retain \"the freedom to choose what he played, and in what picture.\"  (Ostrum and Becker remained friends through at least 1996.)<ref name=\"1996 GMMTB\" />  In January 2018, Ostrum said he sometimes misses acting\u2014though not its [[hurry up and wait|hurry-up-and-wait]] nature\u2014but feels he dodged having to make the transition from child- to adult-actor.<ref name=\"2018-01-28 WDT\" />\n\n{{as of|2018|01}}, Ostrum still received US$8\u20139 <!-- (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|8|2018}}\u2013{{Inflation|US|9|2018}} in {{Inflation/year|US}}) -->of [[royalty payment]]s about every three months.<ref name=\"2018-01-28 WDT\" />\n\n===Lasting effect===\n[[File:Child cast of Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory at the 2011 Wizard World Chicago (cropped).JPG|thumb|Ostrum (second from left) in 2011 with the ''Willy Wonka'' child cast|alt=Five middle-aged Caucasoid adults (two women and three men) in casual dress are behind a table, posing for a group photo.]]\nIn his [[senior (education)|senior year]], Ostrum was involved in film class and, at the interest of one of his instructors, looked back into theatre and acting.  After auditioning for, but not landing, several roles<ref name=\"nwtbaa\" /> (including for [[Alan Strang]]<ref name=\"1996 GMMTB\" /> in [[Equus (play)|''Equus'']] on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]), Ostrum decided not to pursue it further.<ref name=\"nwtbaa\">{{cite web\n| first       =Peter\n| last        =Ostrum\n| title       ='Never Wanted to Be an Actor'\n| url         =https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4757256\n| publisher   =[[NPR]]\n| location    =New York City, U.S.\n| accessdate  =2009-10-11\n}}</ref>  After putting his short film career behind him, Ostrum declined reporters and interviews, preferring not to speak on the subject;<ref name=\"avma20001101\" /> \"I wanted people to judge me on who I was, not what I\u2019d done\".<ref name=\"DEX20110410\">{{cite news\n |title       = Whatever Happened to Willy Wonka's Children?\n |first       = Bridgit\n |last        = Grant\n |url         = http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/239837/Whatever-happened-to-Willy-Wonka-s-children-\n |newspaper   = [[Daily Express]]\n |publisher   = [[Northern & Shell]]\n |location    = London, UK\n |accessdate  = 2011-04-10\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20121005034157/http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/239837/Whatever-happened-to-Willy-Wonka-s-children-\n |archivedate = 2012-10-05\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>  For some time, Ostrum even lied and told people that his brother, and not he, had starred in the film.<ref name=\"2005-07-18 MSNBC\" />  It took Ostrum years after moving to Lowville before he told anybody there about his one-time stardom; even his wife Loretta did not know about his role until he warned her about it just before she met his mother.<ref name=\"20050717npr\" />\n\nSince 1990, Ostrum has since spoken to students at Lowville Academy once a year&mdash;on the last day of school, as a special treat&mdash;about his experience in ''Willy Wonka'' as well as his work in veterinary medicine.<ref name=\"2005-07-18 MSNBC\" />  The students chiefly ask about the film's special effects, and Ostrum describes to them \"what happened to Veruca, how did Violet blow up like a blueberry, how did Charlie fly with Grandpa Joe, all those types of questions.\"<ref name=\"20050717npr\" />  Ostrum also accepted an invitation to appear at the 2018 [[Snowtown Film Festival]] in [[Watertown (city), New York|Watertown, New York]], answering audience questions after a screening of the film; \"it\u2019s in my backyard\u2014it's become a popular event in January and I like to support local events.\"  Ostrum said of the 2018 event that he enjoyed re-watching the film, and that people ask him \"great questions.\"<ref name=\"2018-01-28 WDT\" />  Ostrum has been called \"the most famous man in Lowville\", where the local [[video rental shop]] has twice worn out its [[VHS]] copy of ''Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory''.<ref name=\"2005-07-18 MSNBC\" />\n\nIn the run-up to the release of [[Charlie and the Chocolate Factory (film)|''Charlie and the Chocolate Factory'']] in 2005, Ostrum garnered a spate of attention that included seeing the film in New York City with [[NPR]] as well as being included in [[VH1]]'s list of \"100 Greatest Kid Stars\" (at 78th).<ref name=\"2005-07-18 MSNBC\" />  On the new film, Ostrum quoted fellow ''Wonka'' actor [[Julie Dawn Cole]], saying that \"It's sort of like going back to a house that you once lived in and it's been redecorated.\"  Ultimately, the media attention was so pervasive that Ostrum stopped answering his phone, and requested \"please, no more interviews.\"<ref name=\"20050717npr\" />\n\nIn January 2009, Ostrum teamed up with [[Dunkin' Donuts]] to hand out free rides on the [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]] (MBTA) at [[South Station]] in [[Boston]]; Ostrum's participation connected the MBTA's [[CharlieCard]]s he was handing out with his portrayal of Charlie Bucket in ''Willy Wonka''.  The promotion also gave out one \"golden ticket\", worth unlimited rides on MBTA and unlimited Dunkin' Donuts coffee for 2009.<ref name=\"DDyoutube\">{{cite video\n |people      = Ostrum, Peter; McCall Gosselin\n |date        = 2009-01-23\n |title       = Wonka's Charlie Bucket says to Boston commuters, \"You Kin' Do It!\"\n |url         = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iY6PfkhWQM0\n |format      = [[YouTube]]\n |publisher   = [[Dunkin' Donuts]]\n |location    = [[Canton, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n |accessdate  = 2009-11-13\n |archivedate = 2016-05-11\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20160511214653/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iY6PfkhWQM0\n |url-status     = dead\n}}\n</ref>\n\nIn October 2000, Ostrum and some of his co-stars from the film were scheduled to record an audio commentary for a special edition [[DVD]].<ref name=\"avma20001101\" />  In a 2010 interview, ''Wonka'' co-star [[Denise Nickerson]] (Violet Beauregarde) revealed that Ostrum had agreed to join her and [[Paris Themmen]] (''Wonka''{{'}}s Mike Teevee) for a reunion commemorating the 40th anniversary of the film's release in 2011.<ref name=\"NWIT20100928\">{{cite news\n |title       = 'Willy Wonka' child actress feeling better-than-blue about future film reunion\n |first       = Phil\n |last        = Potempa\n |url         = http://www.nwitimes.com/entertainment/columnists/offbeat/article_65aae4df-5683-5f3f-816a-2bef3f41d952.html\n |newspaper   = [[The Times of Northwest Indiana]]\n |publisher   = [[Lee Enterprises]]\n |location    = [[Munster, Indiana]], U.S.\n |date        = 2010-09-28\n |accessdate  = 2011-01-14\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120927065647/http://www.nwitimes.com/entertainment/columnists/offbeat/article_65aae4df-5683-5f3f-816a-2bef3f41d952.html\n |archivedate = 2012-09-27\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n==Veterinary career==\n{{quote box\n | quote  =I can remember the veterinarian coming out and taking care of the horses, and it made a huge impression on me, [...] This person really enjoyed what he did for a living.  My father was a lawyer, and I really didn't have a clue what he did all day.  But I knew exactly what the veterinarian did.  Someone making a living from something he enjoyed so much really sparked my interest.\n | source =2000 interview with Peter Ostrum<ref name=\"avma20001101\" />\n | width  =30%\n | align  =right\n | salign = right\n}}\nSoon after Ostrum returned home from filming ''Willy Wonka'', his family acquired a horse; while the teenaged Ostrum was interested in the horse, it was the animal's veterinarian that left a lasting impression on him.  Taking a hiatus from school between [[secondary school|high school]] and [[college]], Ostrum [[groom (profession)|groomed]] horses and worked at the Delaware Equine Center in [[Pennsylvania]].  Ostrum contemplated a return to [[Hollywood]], and even visited [[California]] for a week to \"test the waters\" there.  He ultimately decided to pursue a degree in [[veterinary medicine]] instead, feeling that he would forever berate himself if he didn't.  In 1984, Peter Ostrum received his [[veterinary physician|Doctorate of Veterinary Medicine]] from [[Cornell University College of Veterinary Medicine]].<ref name=\"avma20001101\" />\n\n{{as of|2019|08}}, Ostrum worked in [[Lowville (village), New York|Lowville, New York]] both as a veterinarian with the Countryside Veterinary Clinic (working mainly with horses and cows),<ref name=VetNews/><ref name=\"CVCLLP\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.cvcpets.com/our-doctors.pml\n |title       = Our Doctors\n |publisher   = Countryside Veterinary Clinic, LLP\n |location    = [[Lowville (village), New York|Lowville, New York]]\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170807030851/http://www.cvcpets.com/our-doctors.pml\n |archivedate = 2017-08-07\n |accessdate  = 2019-08-19\n |url-status    = live\n}}</ref> and a [[managing partner]] with Dairy Health & Management Services.<ref name=\"Dairy Health & Management Services\" />  Ostrum also took part in ''Veterinarians on Call'', a [[Pfizer]]-funded video series that highlighted the work of large animal veterinarians.<ref name=VetNews>{{cite web|url=http://veterinarynews.dvm360.com/dvm/article/articleDetail.jsp?id=754731&sk=&date=&pageID=3|work=veterinarynews.dvm360.com|title=Vets take the stage in new reality series|author=Stephanie Fellenstein |date=1 Jan 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503133209/http://veterinarynews.dvm360.com/dvm/article/articleDetail.jsp?id=754731&sk=&date=&pageID=3|archivedate=May 3, 2014|publisher=DVM360 Magazine}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<!-- dated references; sorted chronologically -->\n\n<ref name=\"1996 GMMTB\">{{cite book |last1=Kurtti |first1=Jeff |year=1996 |chapter=Chapter Six: Willy Wonka and the Chocolate Factory |title=The Great Movie Musical Trivia Book |location=[[New York City]] |publisher=[[Hal Leonard Corporation|Applause Books]] |pages=[https://archive.org/details/greatmoviemusica00kurt/page/103 103\u2013120] |isbn=1-55783-222-6 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/greatmoviemusica00kurt/page/103 }}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"2005-07-18 MSNBC\">{{cite news |date=2005-07-18 |title=Original Charlie Bucket keeps low profile |url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/8545067/ |url-status=dead |work=[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]] |location=[[Lowville (village), New York|Lowville, New York]] |publisher=[[MSNBC]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121124073720/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/8545067/ |archive-date=2012-11-24 |access-date=2018-10-30 |quote=Peter Ostrum turned down three-picture deal after original 'Wonka'}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"2006-01-03 DMN\">{{cite news |last1=Cavazos |first1=Norma |date=2006-01-03 |title=Television Q&A |work=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |issn=1553-846X}}</ref>\n\n<!-- <ref name=\"2010-04-23 Watertown Daily Times\">{{cite news |date=2010-04-23 |title=South Lewis Central School class leaders |url=http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/article/20100423/CURR04/304239991 |url-status=live |work=Watertown Daily Times |location=[[Turin, New York]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120223083216/http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/article/20100423/CURR04/304239991 |archive-date=2012-02-23 |access-date=2018-07-27 }}</ref> -->\n\n<ref name=\"2011 I Want It Now\">{{cite book |last1=Cole |first1=Julie Dawn |author-link1=Julie Dawn Cole |last2=Esslinger |first2=Michael |year=2011 |chapter=Munich |title=I Want It Now! |edition=First |location=[[Duncan, Oklahoma]] |publisher=BearManor Media |pages=52\u201354 |isbn=978-1-59393-074-5 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"2016-08-30 Variety\">{{cite magazine |last1=Lang |first1=Brent |date=2016-08-30 |title=Actor Who Played Charlie in \u2018Willy Wonka\u2019 on Gene Wilder Death: \u2018It\u2019s Like Losing a Parent\u2019 |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/gene-wilder-willy-wonka-peter-ostrum-1201847688/ |url-status=live |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |language=en |issn=0042-2738 |oclc=810134503 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203030611/https://variety.com/2016/film/news/gene-wilder-willy-wonka-peter-ostrum-1201847688/ |archive-date=2019-02-03 |access-date=2019-02-04}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"2018-01-28 WDT\">{{cite news |last1=Avallone |first1=Elaine M. |date=2018-01-28 |title=Dr. Ostrum relates to being Charlie Bucket following showing of film |url=http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/news03/dr-ostrum-relates-to-being-charlie-bucket-following-showing-of-film-20180128 |url-status=live |work=[[Watertown Daily Times]] |location=[[Watertown (city), New York|Watertown, New York]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309055736/http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/news03/dr-ostrum-relates-to-being-charlie-bucket-following-showing-of-film-20180128 |archive-date=2018-03-09 |access-date=2018-03-10}}</ref>\n\n<!-- undated sources sorted alphabetically -->\n\n<ref name=\"Dairy Health & Management Services\">{{cite web |url=http://dairyhealth.co/our-team/ |title=Our Team |publisher=Dairy Health & Management Services |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819152841/http://dairyheal