n3.jpg|\n   | alt2      = Coat of arms of Bern superimposed over crossed rifles and wreaths. Swiss cross above. Legend and date along edge, denomination below.\n   | caption2  = Reverse\n  }}\n\n*'''Year:''' 1885\n*'''Location:''' Bern\n*'''Denomination:''' 5 francs\n*'''Designer(s):''' Edouard Durussel, Christian B\u00fchler\n*'''Diameter:''' {{convert|37|mm|in|2|abbr=on}}\n*'''Coinage metal:''' Silver\n*'''Mintage:''' 25,000<ref name=\"bern2\">Richter, p. 62</ref>\n*'''Notes:''' Examples are known to have been struck in white metal.<ref name=\"bern2\"/>\n{|class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\" border=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+Bern specifications\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:5em;\"|\n!scope=\"col\"|Inscription\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:40%;\"|Translation\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Obverse\n|''DEM BUND ZUM SCHUTZ DEM FEIND ZUM TRUTZ''\n|The Federation to protect, the enemy to defy\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Reverse\n|''EIDGEN\u00d6SSISCHES SCH\u00dcTZENFEST IN BERN 1885 \u2013 5 Fr.''\n|Federal shooting festival in Bern 1885 \u2013 5 francs\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Edge\n|None\n|None\n|}\n\n=== 1930s series ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"100%\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+Later thalers with event location and year, showing denomination, metal, number struck and ''Standard Catalog of World Coins'' reference number\n!scope=\"col\"|Location\n!scope=\"col\"|Date \n!scope=\"col\"|Denomination\n!scope=\"col\"|Coinage metal\n!scope=\"col\"|Mintage<ref>Bruce, pp. 456\u2013460</ref>\n!scope=\"col\"|KM number\n!scope=\"col\"|Haberling number\n|-<!--Hidden spans help when sorting (so 5 doesn't come after 500). -->\n!scope=\"row\"| Fribourg\n| 1934\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| <span style=\"display:none\">00005</span>5 francs\n| Silver\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 40,650\n| S18\n| H20a\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Fribourg\n| 1934\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| <span style=\"display:none\">00100</span>100 francs\n| Gold\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 2,000\n| S19\n| H21\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Lucerne\n| 1939\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| <span style=\"display:none\">00005</span>5 francs\n| Silver\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 40,000\n| S20\n| H22\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Lucerne\n| 1939\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| <span style=\"display:none\">00100</span>100 francs\n| Gold\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 6,000\n| S21\n| H23\n|}\n\n===1985 to present===\nSeven ''Eidgen\u00f6ssische Sch\u00fctzenfeste'' were held between 1949 and 1977 without the issue of shooting thalers.\nSince 1985, the federal festival has been held regularly every five years. \n\n=== Feldschiessen (1984 to present)===\nBeginning in 1984,  privately issued commemorative silver medals, also colloquially termed ''Sch\u00fctzentaler'', have been issued for the annual ''Eidgen\u00f6ssische Feldschiessen'' (not to be confused with the ''Eidgen\u00f6ssisches Sch\u00fctzenfest'' held only every five years).\nEvery year since has seen the mintage of two coins, each bearing the same design, one struck in silver, the other in gold. \nThe only exceptions are the issues of [[Z\u00fcrich]] and [[Sion, Switzerland|Sion]] in 1999, one of which was struck in [[cupronickel|copper\u2013nickel]], two in silver and two in gold. Until 1995, silver issues were denominated at fifty francs, while gold pieces were denominated at 1,000 francs. Later, gold issues were denominated at 500 francs, excepting only the Z\u00fcrich issues of 1999.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"100%\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+Later thalers with event location and year, showing denomination, metal, number struck and ''Standard Catalog of World Coins'' reference number\n!scope=\"col\"|Location\n!scope=\"col\"|Date \n!scope=\"col\"|Denomination\n!scope=\"col\"|Coinage metal\n!scope=\"col\"|Mintage<ref>Bruce, pp. 456\u2013460</ref>\n!scope=\"col\"|KM number\n!scope=\"col\"|Haberling number\n|-<!--Hidden spans help when sorting (so 5 doesn't come after 500). -->\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Oberhasli\n| 1984\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| <span style=\"display:none\">00050</span>50 francs\n| Silver\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 6,300\n| S22\n| H24a & H24b\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Oberhasli\n| 1984\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| <span style=\"display:none\">01000</span>1,000 francs\n| Gold\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 300\n| S23\n| H25\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Altdorf, Uri|Altdorf]]\n| 1985\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| <span style=\"display:none\">00050</span>50 francs\n| Silver\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 3,500\n| S24\n| H26a\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Altdorf, Uri|Altdorf]]\n| 1985\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| <span style=\"display:none\">01000</span>1,000 francs\n| Gold\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 300\n| S25\n| H27\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Appenzell]]\n| 1986\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| <span style=\"display:none\">00050</span>50 francs\n| Silver\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 3,700\n| S26\n| H28a\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Appenzell]]\n| 1986\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| <span style=\"display:none\">01000</span>1,000 francs\n| Gold\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 300\n| S27\n| H29\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Glarus\n| 1987\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| <span style=\"display:none\">00050</span>50 francs\n| Silver\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 3,200\n| S28\n| H1a\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Glarus\n| 1987\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| <span style=\"display:none\">01000</span>1,000 francs\n| Gold\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 300\n| S29\n| H32\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Brugg]]\n| 1988\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| <span style=\"display:none\">00050</span>50 francs\n| Silver\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 3,000\n| S30\n| H33a & H33b\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Brugg]]\n| 1988\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| <span style=\"display:none\">01000</span>1,000 francs\n| Gold\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 400\n| S31\n| H34\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Menzingen]]\n| 1989\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| <span style=\"display:none\">00050</span>50 francs\n| Silver\n| sty